</div>I am. I stopped after a week when I hit 50.<br />
<br />
A lot of the enjoyment I get in mmorpgs is to progress the character. Without progress it is all down to the story. And even though I enjoy several of the questlines and story lines, lets be honest and say that the actual story (written/spoken) in a quest that requires 5+ hours worth of dungeon crawling is 4-5 minutes at best. The other 4 hours and 55 minutes are killing, looting, exploring, whatever. <br />
Past 50 the vast majority of the things you do offer no rewards what so ever for those 4 hours and 55 minutes, other than perhaps the interaction with group members (if the quest is solo... bleh).<br />
<br />
Rewards in LOTRO are substantial at first, but once you get to 47 and get access to crafted light blue gear which everyone can get trivially, upgrades are few and far between. Majority of quests, including hard group quests, have rewards that are only worth the silver they vendor for. So you can put 10 hours into a questline and get a total earning of 0 exp and 50s for selling a light blue sword worse than the one you got. <br />
<br />
There are tons of quests I haven't done, there is lots of content. I enjoyed doing the content. I just don't see a purpose to doing it anymore. Once they add new levels, I'll be back in an instant. If they had any sort of AA points or such, I'd still be playing it.</div>
